{"parse":{"title":"Her Hidden Children","pageid":35005834,"revid":798351870,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><caption style=\"font-style:italic;padding-bottom:0.2em;\">Her Hidden Children: The Rise of Wicca and Paganism in America <span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Her+Hidden+Children%3A+The+Rise+of+Wicca+and+Paganism+in+America&amp;rft.author=%5B%5BChas+S.+Clifton%5D%5D&amp;rft.date=2005&amp;rft.pub=%5B%5BAltaMira+Press%5D%5D&amp;rft.pages=189\"></span></caption><tbody><tr><td colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center\">\n<a href=\"/wiki/File:Her_Hidden_Children.jpg\" class=\"image\"><img alt=\"Her Hidden Children.jpg\" src=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/a/a5/Her_Hidden_Children.jpg/220px-Her_Hidden_Children.jpg\" width=\"220\" height=\"327\" srcset=\"//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/a/a5/Her_Hidden_Children.jpg 1.5x\" data-file-width=\"259\" data-file-height=\"385\" /></a><div>First edition cover of <i>Her Hidden Children</i>.</div></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Author</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Chas_S._Clifton\" title=\"Chas S. Clifton\">Chas S. Clifton</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Country</th><td>\nUnited States</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Language</th><td>\nEnglish</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Subject</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Religious_studies\" title=\"Religious studies\">Religious studies</a><br /><a href=\"/wiki/Pagan_studies\" title=\"Pagan studies\">Pagan studies</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Publisher</th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/AltaMira_Press\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"AltaMira Press\">AltaMira Press</a></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><div style=\"padding:0.1em 0;line-height:1.2em;\">Publication date</div></th><td>\n2005</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Media&#160;type</th><td>\nPrint (<a href=\"/wiki/Hardcover\" title=\"Hardcover\">Hardcover</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Paperback\" title=\"Paperback\">paperback</a>)</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Pages</th><td>\n189</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a></th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/978-0759102026\" title=\"Special:BookSources/978-0759102026\">978-0759102026</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><i><b>Her Hidden Children: The Rise of Wicca and Paganism in America</b></i> is a historical study of <a href=\"/wiki/Wicca\" title=\"Wicca\">Wicca</a> and <a href=\"/wiki/Paganism_(contemporary)\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Paganism (contemporary)\">Contemporary Paganism</a> in the <a href=\"/wiki/United_States\" title=\"United States\">United States</a>. It was written by the American academic <a href=\"/wiki/Chas_S._Clifton\" title=\"Chas S. Clifton\">Chas S. Clifton</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/Colorado_State_University-Pueblo\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Colorado State University-Pueblo\">Colorado State University-Pueblo</a>, and published by <a href=\"/wiki/AltaMira_Press\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"AltaMira Press\">AltaMira Press</a> in 2005.\n</p><p><i>Her Hidden Children</i> was reviewed in a number of academic journals.\n</p>\n<div id=\"toc\" class=\"toc\"><input type=\"checkbox\" role=\"button\" id=\"toctogglecheckbox\" class=\"toctogglecheckbox\" style=\"display:none\" /><div class=\"toctitle\" lang=\"en\" dir=\"ltr\"><h2>Contents</h2><span class=\"toctogglespan\"><label class=\"toctogglelabel\" for=\"toctogglecheckbox\"></label></span></div>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-1\"><a href=\"#Background\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Background</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-2\"><a href=\"#Reception_and_recognition\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">2</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Reception and recognition</span></a></li>\n<li class=\"toclevel-1 tocsection-3\"><a href=\"#References\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3</span> <span class=\"toctext\">References</span></a>\n<ul>\n<li class=\"toclevel-2 tocsection-4\"><a href=\"#Bibliography\"><span class=\"tocnumber\">3.1</span> <span class=\"toctext\">Bibliography</span></a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Background\">Background</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Her_Hidden_Children&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Background\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In 1999, the English historian <a href=\"/wiki/Ronald_Hutton\" title=\"Ronald Hutton\">Ronald Hutton</a> of the <a href=\"/wiki/University_of_Bristol\" title=\"University of Bristol\">University of Bristol</a> had published his own study of Wiccan history, <i><a href=\"/wiki/The_Triumph_of_the_Moon\" title=\"The Triumph of the Moon\">The Triumph of the Moon: A History of Modern Pagan Witchcraft</a></i>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Reception_and_recognition\">Reception and recognition</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Her_Hidden_Children&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: Reception and recognition\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>The book received generally positive reviews from a number of academic journals.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Her_Hidden_Children&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist columns references-column-width\" style=\"-moz-column-width: 20em; -webkit-column-width: 20em; column-width: 20em; list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Ashcraft, W. Michael (2007). \"Her Hidden Children: The Rise of Wicca and Paganism in America. (book review)\". <i>Magic, Ritual &amp; Witchcraft</i>. <b>2</b> (1): 82\u201384. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1353/mrw.0.0043\">10.1353/mrw.0.0043</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Serial_Number\" title=\"International Standard Serial Number\">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/issn/1556-8547\">1556-8547</a>. <q>Clifton\u2019s book does not cover everything. He excludes Pagans who look to ancient cultures, like the Celts, for their symbols and rituals. He also leaves out feminist spirituality, which is closely linked to Wicca and Paganism. But he does an admirable job of providing for the first time a formal history of the movement.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Magic%2C+Ritual+%26+Witchcraft&amp;rft.atitle=Her+Hidden+Children%3A+The+Rise+of+Wicca+and+Paganism+in+America.+%28book+review%29&amp;rft.volume=2&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=82-84&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1353%2Fmrw.0.0043&amp;rft.issn=1556-8547&amp;rft.aulast=Ashcraft&amp;rft.aufirst=W.+Michael&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHer+Hidden+Children\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Pizza, Murphy (2007). \"Her hidden children: the rise of Wicca and paganism in America (book review)\". <i>The Pomegranate</i>. <b>9</b> (2): 200\u2013201. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1558/pome.v9i2.200\">10.1558/pome.v9i2.200</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Serial_Number\" title=\"International Standard Serial Number\">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/issn/1528-0268\">1528-0268</a>. <q>Her Hidden Children is an important and welcome contribution to academic and non-scholar Pagans alike.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Pomegranate&amp;rft.atitle=Her+hidden+children%3A+the+rise+of+Wicca+and+paganism+in+America+%28book+review%29&amp;rft.volume=9&amp;rft.issue=2&amp;rft.pages=200-201&amp;rft.date=2007&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1558%2Fpome.v9i2.200&amp;rft.issn=1528-0268&amp;rft.aulast=Pizza&amp;rft.aufirst=Murphy&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHer+Hidden+Children\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Bloch, Jon P (March 2008). \"Her hidden children: the rise of Wicca and paganism in America (book review)\". <i>Journal for the Scientific Study of Religion</i>. <b>47</b> (1): 171\u2013173. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1111/j.1468-5906.2008.00399_8.x\">10.1111/j.1468-5906.2008.00399_8.x</a>. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Serial_Number\" title=\"International Standard Serial Number\">ISSN</a>&#160;<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//www.worldcat.org/issn/0021-8294\">0021-8294</a>. <q>Clifton, an English Professor at Colorado State University, provides an account of the rise of Wicca and Paganism in the United States that focuses not on social upheaval so much as on popular cultural symbols and artifacts, key individuals, and popular texts as instrumental in the said rise...Clifton\u2019s is a book that could enliven courses in popular culture, as well as courses in religion.</q></cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Journal+for+the+Scientific+Study+of+Religion&amp;rft.atitle=Her+hidden+children%3A+the+rise+of+Wicca+and+paganism+in+America+%28book+review%29&amp;rft.volume=47&amp;rft.issue=1&amp;rft.pages=171-173&amp;rft.date=2008-03&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1111%2Fj.1468-5906.2008.00399_8.x&amp;rft.issn=0021-8294&amp;rft.aulast=Bloch&amp;rft.aufirst=Jon+P&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AHer+Hidden+Children\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n</ol></div>\n<h3><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Bibliography\">Bibliography</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Her_Hidden_Children&amp;action=edit&amp;section=4\" title=\"Edit section: Bibliography\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h3>\n<style data-mw-deduplicate=\"TemplateStyles:r853264625\">.mw-parser-output .refbegin{font-size:90%;margin-bottom:0.5em}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>ul{list-style-type:none;margin-left:0}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>ul>li,.mw-parser-output .refbegin-hanging-indents>dl>dd{margin-left:0;padding-left:3.2em;text-indent:-3.2em;list-style:none}.mw-parser-output .refbegin-100{font-size:100%}</style><div class=\"refbegin\" style=\